"Sganga G., Cozza V., Spanu T., Spada P.L., Fadda G.","Global climate change and wound care: Case study of an off-season vibrio alginolyticus infection in a healthy man",2009,"Ostomy Wound Management","55","4",,"60","62",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-67549134498&partnerID=40&md5=1749d5853b51a7d2d54e8bddf43072de","Department of Surgery, Italy; Department of Microbiology, Catholic University of Sacred Heart, Rome, Italy; Catholic University of Sacred Heart, Department of Surgery, Policlinico A. Gemmelli, Largo A. Gemmelli 8, 00168 Roma, Italy","Sganga, G., Department of Surgery, Italy, Catholic University of Sacred Heart, Department of Surgery, Policlinico A. Gemmelli, Largo A. Gemmelli 8, 00168 Roma, Italy; Cozza, V., Department of Surgery, Italy; Spanu, T.; Spada, P.L.; Fadda, G., Department of Microbiology, Catholic University of Sacred Heart, Rome, Italy","Vibrio alginolyticus is a halophilic Gram-negative bacterium normally present in seawater. Vibrios are not capable of cutaneous invasion through intact skin and their isolation from extraintestinal sites is uncommon. However, interruptions in skin integrity (cuts or abrasions) can allow these bacteria to cause complicated skin and soft tissues infections. This case study describes the clinical assessment and management of a nonhealing traumatic wound, sustained in a coastal area during the winter months, in a healthy 70-year-old man. Culture results were positive for V. alginolyticus. Appropriate antibiotic treatment and topical wound care successfully resolved the infection. V. alginolyticus infections are usually benign; respond well to treatment, even with local therapy only; and tend to result from contact with warm ocean water. The clinical characteristics of the wound prompted a suspicion of a Vibrio infection even though the wound was sustained in the winter time and the patient did not have direct contact with ocean water. Although other case studies of Vibrio infections in the absence of direct contact with ocean water have been published, increased ocean temperatures due to global climate changes may explain the out-of-season infection in this patient. Clinicians should monitor the progression of wound healing and be prepared to modify treatment based on individual circumstances, especially in the case of unusual wound presentation, nonhealing, or a progressing wound infection.",,"bacterial DNA; sea water; aged; article; biopsy; case report; genetics; greenhouse effect; human; leg injury; male; methodology; microbiology; penetrating trauma; polymerase chain reaction; risk factor; season; skin care; Vibrio alginolyticus; vibriosis; wound healing; wound infection; Aged; Biopsy; DNA, Bacterial; Greenhouse Effect; Humans; Leg Injuries; Male; Polymerase Chain Reaction; Risk Factors; Seasons; Seawater; Skin Care; Vibrio alginolyticus; Vibrio Infections; Water Microbiology; Wound Healing; Wound Infection; Wounds, Penetrating",,"DNA, Bacterial",,,,"Chakraborty, S., Nair, G.B., Shinoda, S., Pathogenic vibrios in the natural aquatic environment (1997) Reviews on Environmental Health, 12 (2), pp. 63-80; West, P.A., The human pathogenic vibrios - A public health update with environmental perspectives (1989) Epidemiology and Infection, 103 (1), pp. 1-34; Farmer, J.J., Hickman-Brenner, F., (1992) The Genera Vibrio and Photobacterium, pp. 2952-3011. , Balows A, Truper HG, Schleifer KH, e.t. al (eds). The Prokaryotes:A Handbook of the Biology of Bacteria. New York: Springer- Verlag; Schmidt, U., Chmel, H., Cobbs, C., Vibrio alginolyticus infections in humans (1979) Journal of Clinical Microbiology, 10 (5), pp. 666-668; Hornstrup, M.K., Gahrn-Hansen, B., Extraintestinal infections caused by Vibrio parahaemolyticus and Vibrio alginolyticus in a Danish county 1987-1993 (1993) Scan J Infect Dis, 25 (6), pp. 35-740; Schijven, J.F., De Roda Husman, A.M., Effect of climate changes on waterbornedisease in the netherlands (2005) Wat Sci Techn, 51 (5), pp. 78-87. 